        &larr; Back
      </a>
      <span style="display:block;font-family:var(--font-sans);font-size:0.6rem;font-weight:800;letter-spacing:0.2em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#6b4610;margin-bottom:1rem;">Sellers &middot; 5 min read</span>
      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#191817;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Selling in Underwood 2026
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(25,24,23,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Underwood's Marketplace precinct, Mansfield State High catchment and Pacific Motorway access create a distinct southern Brisbane buyer pool. Here is what sellers need to know about timing and positioning in 2026.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Underwood sits approximately 18 kilometres south of the Brisbane CBD, bordered by Springwood, Eight Mile Plains, Wishart, Rochedale South and Mansfield. It is a suburb with a dual identity: a major retail and commercial precinct anchored by Underwood Marketplace and the Logan Road commercial strip, alongside established residential pockets where families have been buying for school catchment access and Pacific Motorway connectivity for decades. Sellers who understand which identity their property belongs to, and who pitch their campaign accordingly, consistently produce better results than those who treat Underwood as a generic southern corridor address.</p>

      <p>The residential pockets north and west of the commercial core are the suburb's strongest performing areas. These streets are genuinely family-oriented, with established trees, larger blocks than the newer estate suburbs to the south, and proximity to Mansfield State High School's catchment boundary that drives consistent demand. The streets closest to the arterial roads or commercial zoning carry a different buyer profile, and they need a different campaign approach.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Who is buying in Underwood</h2>
      <p>Underwood's strongest buyer in 2026 is the family with secondary-school-age children who specifically wants access to Mansfield State High. These buyers have done precise research on the catchment boundary, they know which streets fall inside and which fall just outside, and they are prepared to pay a premium for certainty of access. When a property sits clearly within catchment, naming that fact explicitly in the campaign attracts this buyer reliably. When a property sits close to but outside the boundary, the campaign needs to be positioned differently, around the commercial amenity and motorway access rather than the school.</p>

      <p>A second buyer profile is the family comparing Underwood against Eight Mile Plains and Springwood at similar budgets. These buyers want the combination of a practical retail precinct within walking or short driving distance, Pacific Motorway access in both directions, and a freestanding home with a usable backyard. They are comparing multiple suburbs simultaneously and making a considered decision, not an impulse purchase. A well-positioned campaign that speaks directly to those three motivations generates stronger inquiry than one that leads with generic suburban copy.</p>

      <p>Investors are present in Underwood, particularly in the streets with good rental yields relative to entry price. The suburb's commercial amenity and motorway access make it an attractive investment address for the buy-and-hold investor, and the rental market is consistent. Campaigns aimed primarily at investors should emphasise yield, tenant demand and capital growth context rather than lifestyle factors.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What drives value in Underwood</h2>
      <p>Mansfield State High School catchment is the primary value driver for the family buyer segment. The premium for catchment-inside properties is real and consistent, and it does not disappear in softer market conditions because the motivation is structural rather than speculative. Families making a school-driven purchase decision are buying for a specific life outcome, and they are prepared to pay for it.</p>

      <p>Proximity to Underwood Marketplace is a genuine amenity that buyers in this suburb recognise. The precinct delivers major supermarkets, specialty retail, dining and services within a short drive or walk, which reduces the practical cost and time of daily errands. This matters most to families and to older buyers, and it is a legitimate selling point that should be named concretely rather than described in generic terms.</p>

      <p>Pacific Motorway access is the third consistent driver. Underwood's position allows efficient travel north to the CBD and south to the Gold Coast via the M1, and east to the Gateway Motorway via connecting roads. For households where one or both adults commute in different directions, that flexibility is a meaningful differentiator relative to suburbs where the motorway access is more directionally constrained.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Preparing your Underwood home for sale</h2>
      <p>Underwood's family buyer is comparing your property online against Eight Mile Plains and Springwood before booking an inspection, and the online presentation gap between a well-photographed property and a poorly presented one is as consequential here as in any Brisbane suburban market. The investment in professional photography, basic staging for the main living areas and the outdoor space, and a clean, tidy exterior reliably increases inspection numbers and buyer quality at this price point.</p>

      <p>For properties in the residential pockets, the standard pre-sale preparation applies: address deferred maintenance, repaint where needed, tidy the garden, and clean the hard surfaces. For properties that are close to the commercial precinct or on busier arterial streets, the preparation strategy should include careful photography that honestly represents the property while showcasing its best attributes, and copy that speaks to the buyer who values the amenity proximity rather than quiet residential character. The buyer who is trading a quieter street for walkable convenience exists and is a genuine market in Underwood; the goal is to find them efficiently.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Best time to sell in Underwood</h2>
      <p>Underwood's family buyer market tracks school calendar patterns reliably. The strongest selling windows are autumn from March through May, when buyers who have been researching since before Christmas are ready to make decisions and competing stock is lower than the spring peak, and spring from September through November when inspection volumes are highest. The school catchment buyer in particular tends to want to be settled before the start of a school year, which means a campaign launched in March to April often targets families making a decision for the following January intake. The weakest periods are school holiday windows: January, the mid-year break and the pre-Christmas period. An Underwood property launched in late November is competing against the holiday-season distraction for exactly the family buyers who would otherwise be its strongest competitors.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How long does it take to sell in Underwood</h2>
      <p>Well-presented, accurately priced Underwood homes in good residential positions typically sell within 25 to 40 days. The suburb's buyer pool is motivated and consistent, and properties within the Mansfield State High catchment that are correctly priced attract inquiry quickly. The school catchment buyer in particular acts with more urgency than the general family buyer, because their purchase is tied to a specific life decision rather than a flexible preference. Properties outside catchment or on busier commercial streets take longer: the buyer pool is narrower, and the pricing needs to clearly reflect the trade-offs the buyer is accepting. Accurate pricing relative to Eight Mile Plains and Springwood comparables is the most important variable in campaign speed across all Underwood properties. The southern corridor buyer is well-informed, and an overpriced listing will sit until a price adjustment resets the market's attention.</p>

